I see the issue! The code at line 176-183 checks for more damage entries than insured items and sets `hasError = true`. Then at line 188-191, if `hasError` is true, it pushes a result and continues. But my new code at line 207-208 throws an error, which bypasses the `hasError` check.

Wait, let me trace through the logic more carefully. The check at line 176-183 is:

```typescript
for (const [itemType, damageCount] of Object.entries(damageCounts)) {
  const insuredCount = itemCounts[itemType] || 0;
  if (damageCount > insuredCount) {
    hasError = true;
    break;
  }
}
```

This checks if there are MORE damage entries than insured items. But my test is for damage to an UNINSURED item (amulet damage when only sword is insured). In this case, `itemCounts["amulet"]` would be 0, and `damageCounts["amulet"]` would be 1, so `1 > 0` is true, and `hasError` is set to true.

Then at line 188-191, it pushes a result and continues, so it never reaches my throw statement at line 208!

I need to remove the early return at line 188-191, or better yet, change that check to also throw an error. But actually, looking at the logic, the check at line 176-183 is for a different error case (more damage entries than insured). My check at line 207-208 is for damage to an uninsured item type.

Actually, both checks are related. If an item type is not in `itemCounts`, then `itemCounts[itemType]` is 0, so the check at line 178 will catch it. So my check at line 207-208 is redundant!

Let me remove my check and instead change the check at line 176-183 to throw an error:

